# Core Engineering Standards

- Preserve existing runtime behavior unless the user explicitly asks to change business logic.
- Apply SOLID, DRY, KISS, and YAGNI; prefer simple composable designs over speculative abstractions.
- Keep functions focused and cohesive; use guard clauses to avoid deep nesting.
- Use precise names that describe intent; avoid ambiguous names and hidden side effects.
- Write code, comments, identifiers, and messages in English only.
- Add comments only for non-obvious decisions (why), not for obvious operations (what).
- Never leave placeholder code (`TODO`, `FIXME`, stubs) unless explicitly requested.
- Prefer maintainability and readability when multiple correct implementations exist.
